ASSIGNMENT, CO-TENANCY, AND SHARED FACILITIES AGREEMENT
This Assignment, Co-Tenancy, and Shared Facilities Agreement is made and entered into by and among DEERFIELD WIND ENERGY, LLC, a Delaware limited company (“Deerfield”), and DEERFIELD WIND ENERGY 2, LLC, a Delaware limited company (“Deerfield 2”) and DEERFIELD WIND ENERGY 2, LLC, a Delaware limited company (the “Co-Tenancy Manager”), (Deerfield, Deerfield 2 and Co-Tenancy Manager may be referred to collectively as the “Parties” and each individually, a “Party”), dated as of _, 2022 (the “Contract Date”). Deerfield and Deerfield 2 may also be referred to herein as “Co-Tenants” and each as “Co-Tenant.” Certain capitalized terms used in this Agreement are given defined meanings in Appendix A attached hereto.
R E C I T A L S:
A. Deerfield owns and operates a 149-megawatt (“MW”) wind power project that is located in Huron County, Michigan (the “Deerfield Project”).
B. Deerfield 2 is currently developing a wind power project with an anticipated design capacity of 112.1 MW (“MW”) that will be located in Huron County, Michigan (the “Deerfield 2 Project”).
C. The Deerfield Project and the Deerfield 2 Project are herein sometimes referred to individually as a “Project” or collectively as the “Projects”.
D. Deerfield has obtained those multi-purpose easements or leasehold interests described on Exhibit A-1 (the “Easements”) that include the right to construct and maintain collection and transmission facilities on the real property described therein.
E. Deerfield and Deerfield 2 executed that certain Partial Assignment of Co-Tenancy Interest
in Shared Premises on
April 11, 2022
, recorded on
in the official public records
of Huron County, Michigan as Liber , Page _ , wherein Deerfield partially assigned the Easements to Deerfield 2 (the “Partial Assignment”).
F. Deerfield and Deerfield 2 executed that certain Covenant Deed on
April 11, 2022 ,
recorded on _ in the official public records of Huron County, Michigan as Liber , Page , wherein Deerfield conveyed an undivided one-half interest in the property identified as the O&M Parcel on Exhibit A-2 (the “O&M Parcel”) and the operations and maintenance building located thereon that houses spare parts, equipment, and maintenance personnel (the “O&M Building”).
G. Deerfield has constructed (i) certain infrastructure, including poles capable of supporting two 120 kV electric transmission lines (the “Poles”) and two 120 kV transmission lines on the Poles (the “Lines”). One of the Lines is being used for the purpose of interconnecting the Deerfield Project to the Point of Interconnection (as defined herein). Deerfield has also constructed the O&M Building on the O&M Parcel. As described herein, the Deerfield 2 Project will be using one of the Lines and constructing certain infrastructure to be used for the purpose of interconnecting the Deerfield 2 Project to the Point of Interconnection and will be sharing use of the O&M Building.
H. Pursuant to the Consent, Crossing and Option Agreement executed by Deerfield and DTE dated September 29, 2015 (“Option Agreement”), Deerfield and DTE have agreed that DTE may exercise the Option (as defined in the Option Agreement) and purchase, own and use the Option Line (as defined in the Option Agreement) and join this Agreement upon the terms set forth therein and herein, upon exercising the Option.
I. Deerfield assigned and conveyed or will assign and convey to Deerfield 2, subject to the terms and conditions set forth herein, an undivided tenants-in-common interest in the Shared Facilities.
J. The location of the Shared Facilities and Real Property Interests are depicted on Exhibit A-3.
K. The Co-Tenants now owning or hereafter acquiring an interest as Co-Tenants as more particularly described in Article 1 of this Agreement desire to set forth herein the rights and obligations of the Co-Tenants with respect to the Shared Facilities and the Real Property Interests, and the cost, use and maintenance thereof.
L. The Co-Tenants desire to engage the Co-Tenancy Manager to provide operation and maintenance services to the Co-Tenants for the Shared Facilities and Co-Tenancy Manager desires to provide such services for the Co-Tenants in accordance with the terms hereof.
NOW, THEREFORE, in consideration of the foregoing recitals, the mutual promises contained herein, and for other good and valuable consideration, the receipt and adequacy of which are hereby acknowledged by the Parties and the Co-Tenancy Manager, the Parties and the Co-Tenancy Manager agree as follows:
SHARED FACILITIES
1.1 Grant of Co-Tenancy Interest between Deerfield and Deerfield 2. Upon and subject to the terms, conditions, restrictions and reservations set forth herein, in the Partial Assignment of Co-Tenancy Interest in Shared Premises dated as of the date hereof between the Parties, and in the Easements, Deerfield does hereby grant, bargain, sell, remise, release, alien, convey and confirm to Deerfield 2 an undivided Pro-Rata Share in and to the Easements and the Shared Facilities (the “Conveyance”), while at the same time reserving unto itself an undivided Pro-Rated ownership interest in and to the Easements and the Shared Facilities. The Conveyance is made “AS IS” (such “as-is” condition to include all applicable Governmental Requirements) and WITHOUT WARRANTY, SPECIFICALLY INCLUDING WITHOUT WARRANTY OF TITLE, EITHER EXPRESSED OR IMPLIED, INCLUDING, WITHOUT LIMITATION, ANY WARRANTIES ARISING BY COMMON LAW OR STATUTE. As a result of the Conveyances, each Co-Tenant shall hold an Undivided Interest, in the amounts set forth above, in and to the Real Property and Shared Facilities as Tenants-in-Common.
1.2 Grant of Co-Tenancy Interest to Joining Co-Tenant(s). On or after the Contract Date, any third Party, including DTE, seeking to acquire an interest in the Shared Facilities (for purposes of this Agreement, each a “Joining Co-Tenant” until and upon satisfaction of the conditions and requirements set forth in this Agreement at which point such Party shall become a
“Co-Tenant”) shall deliver a written notice to all existing Co-Tenants with an interest in the Shared Facilities (collectively with any Party or Parties with an existing interest in the Shared Facilities, a “Granting Co-Tenant”) of the Joining Co-Tenant’s intention to acquire an undivided interest in the Shared Facilities equal to such Joining Co-Tenant’s Pro-Rata share in and to the Shared Facilities. Upon the Majority Approval by the Co-Tenants of the Joining Co-Tenant, the Granting Co-Tenant will execute and deliver to such Joining Co-Tenant a (1) Assignment and Assumption Agreement of the Shared Facilities that are not Easements, (2) assignment of a partial interest in the Easements so that each Joining Co-Tenant and each Granting Co-Tenant will hold its Pro-Rata share in the Easements, (3) any additional agreements the Granting Co-Tenant will assign to the Joining Co-Tenant, and (4) transfer tax declarations, owner’s affidavits and such other reasonable and customary transfer documents required in connection with the transfer of a real property interest or that will facilitate the Joining Co-Tenant’s ability to obtain owners’ and lenders’ title insurance with respect to the Easements to the extent that such documents do not decrease any Party’s rights and do not increase the obligations of any Party, all of which shall be prepared and paid for at the Joining Co-Tenant’s expense. Upon closing of these above-described conveyances, the Granting Co-Tenant and the Joining Co-Tenant shall each be considered Co-Tenants. Notwithstanding the foregoing, in the event that any third party, including DTE, becomes a Joining Co-Tenant, the Shared Facilities shall, thereafter, not include the O&M Building or the O&M Parcel, which shall continue to be owned by Deerfield and Deerfield 2, as tenants in common, and shall be governed by a separate written agreement.
1.3 Easements. Each Co-Tenant has the right to use the Easements and the O&M Parcel in a manner consistent with its Undivided Interest therein, as provided herein, and agrees that it will not take any action that results in a breach of the terms on any of the Easements.
1.4 Ownership and Use of Interests in Shared Facilities. The Co-Tenants each have the right to hold and utilize its Undivided Interest jointly, as tenants-in-common, subject to the terms of this Agreement, to the full extent necessary for each Project to operate at its capacity. Without limiting the generality of the foregoing, the tenants-in-common rights of each Co-Tenant shall include the joint use of the Shared Facilities (whether now existing or hereafter constructed) to the full extent necessary for each Project to operate at its capacity and to the extent such Shared Facilities (whether now existing or hereafter constructed) constitute fixtures under applicable law.
1.5 Maintenance of the Shared Facilities. The Co-Tenants hereby engage the Co-Tenancy Manager to, and the Co-Tenancy Manager agrees to, perform and provide with respect to the Shared Facilities all operational maintenance responsibilities in accordance with the standards set forth in Section 4.2. The Co-Tenancy Manager’s responsibilities include those set forth in Exhibit B (the “Shared Facilities Maintenance”). The costs and expenses of the Shared Facilities Maintenance shall be incurred or reimbursed as set forth in Article 3 below, such that Co-Tenants shall share equally in costs and expenses of maintenance of Shared Facilities.
1.6 Additional Facilities and Rights.
(a) If a Co-Tenant determines that additional facilities, improvements, modifications, or upgrades of facilities on any Shared Facilities (the “Additional Facilities”) are required by such Co-Tenant, specifically including, without limitation, any Additional Facilities for the transmission of electricity, the Co-Tenant requiring such Additional Facilities shall have
the responsibility for procuring and installing such Additional Facilities and obtaining all necessary approvals from applicable Governmental Authorities at such Co-Tenant’s sole cost and expense (unless, as provided in Section 1.6(b) or (c), it is determined in accordance with Prudent Industry Practice that such Additional Facilities materially benefit another Co-Tenant’s Project, in which case such Additional Facilities shall be a joint expense of the Co-Tenants materially benefiting from such Additional Facilities).
(b) If a Co-Tenant determines that such Additional Facilities are required for its Project, such Co-Tenant may give written notice to the other Co-Tenant(s) of such requirement, with a detailed explanation setting forth why such Additional Facilities are needed. The Co-Tenant(s) receiving such notice shall have thirty (30) days following receipt of such notice to determine if such Additional Facilities are also needed for its Project and to so notify the requesting Co-Tenant in writing of its election to participate in such Additional Facilities. Failure to notify the requesting Co-Tenant of its election to participate in the acquisition of such Additional Facilities within thirty (30) days after receiving such notice shall be deemed an election not to participate. Any Additional Facilities needed by one or more, but not all, of the Co-Tenants may be acquired and held in the name of such individual Co-Tenant as such Co-Tenant’s Separate Facilities or in the name of such Co-Tenants who elect to participate in such Additional Facilities as such Co-Tenants’ Shared Premises held in undivided ownership interests equal to such Co-Tenants’ Undivided Interest.
(c) Upon acquisition of any Additional Facilities to be used by two or more Parties pursuant to this Section 1.6, a copy of the agreement(s) underlying the Additional Facilities shall be delivered to the Co-Tenancy Manager.
1.7 Warranty Claims. The Co-Tenancy Manager and each Co-Tenant installing, or causing to be installed, Shared Facilities or Replacement Components shall exercise such Party’s rights under the contractor and vendor warranties with respect to the Shared Facilities, and upon the reasonable request of the applicable Co-Tenants and subject to their direction and control, the Co-Tenancy Manager shall assist them with the exercise of such rights. The Co-Tenancy Manager shall (i) monitor and report to the Co-Tenants concerning the remaining terms of any warranties on Shared Facilities; (ii) perform such inspections as are reasonable to ensure that any final warranty work is not required prior to the expiration of any such warranty, and (iii) subject to the direction and control of the applicable Co-Tenants, prepare and prosecute warranty claims on behalf of such Co-Tenants, if reasonably necessary to enforce any such warranties. Subject to the direction and control of the applicable Co-Tenants, the Co-Tenancy Manager shall be primarily responsible for administering the prosecution of the warranty claims requirements under this Section 1.5 on behalf of the Co-Tenants and each of the Co-Tenants shall cooperate with each other with respect to such warranty claims to the extent such Co-Tenants are the owners and holders of the warranties. All reasonable expenses incurred by the Co-Tenancy Manager or any Co-Tenant in pursuing such warranty claims shall be allocated to the Co-Tenants subject to reimbursement by each applicable Co-Tenant in accordance with the manner by which the Parties share Shared O&M Expenses in and to the applicable Shared Facilities pursuant to Article 3 below.
ACCESS, NONINTERFERENCE; NATURE OF RELATIONSHIP; WAIVER OF PARTITION
2.1 Access to the Shared Facilities. Subject to the terms and limitations set forth in this Agreement, each Co-Tenant and its contractors and designees shall have unrestricted temporary access to the Shared Facilities (it being understood that the operation and maintenance of the Shared Facilities shall be performed solely by the Co-Tenancy Manager as provided hereunder). Notwithstanding the preceding sentence, except in the event of an Emergency, each Party shall give the Co-Tenancy Manager Representative at least 48-hours prior notice of its intent to permit its contractors or designees to access the Shared Facilities (such notice may be by telephone, e-mail, or any other recognized electronic means in addition to any other methods of notice authorized herein), and each Party shall follow, and cause its contractors, designees to follow, all written safety and security procedures adopted by the Co-Tenancy Manager with the approval of the Co-Tenants. In the event of an Emergency, prior notice is not required, but a Party shall give notice of entry on the Real Property as soon as reasonably practicable thereafter.
2.2 No Interference.
(a) Each Party’s use of any Shared Facilities shall, to the fullest extent commercially reasonable and subject to Prudent Industry Practices, (i) limit any interference with the use and enjoyment by the other Parties of their rights in and to the Shared Facilities, (ii) except in the event of an Emergency schedule during an off-peak and/or low wind down-time period any maintenance and repair activities to such Party’s Project in order to minimize the impact on the Project of the other Party, and (iii) provide prior written notice to the other Party of commencement of such maintenance and repair activities together with a reasonably detailed description thereof, including dates and times of such maintenance and repair activities, and any disconnection of the Shared Facilities that could reasonably be required.
(b) Each Party shall reimburse the other Party for all Net Revenue Losses accruing during the period of disconnection arising due to the owner of a Project’s construction or maintenance activities, use of the Shared Facilities, or entry upon any Shared Facilities, it being hereby agreed that payment of the Net Revenue Losses shall be the Co-Tenant’s sole and exclusive remedy with respect to loss of revenue and other Consequential Damages due to the period of disconnection. The Parties agree that the actual Consequential Damages arising due to such period of disconnection would be difficult to compute and that Net Revenue Losses is a good faith estimate of the calculations utilized to determine the actual Consequential Damages that would be suffered.
(c) Each Co-Tenant shall have the right to transmit electrical power from its Project through its Separate Facilities and to use the Shared Facilities in connection with such generation and transmission of electricity from its Project.
2.3 Covenants Running with the Land. The covenants of the Parties made in this Agreement and the exhibits attached to this Agreement shall be deemed to be covenants running with and binding upon the Parties’ interest in the Real Property pursuant to applicable law for the duration of the Term.
2.4 Nature of Relationship Between Parties. The Parties and Co-Tenancy Manager do not intend by this Agreement to create a partnership or a joint venture, but merely to set forth the terms and conditions upon which each of them shall hold their respective interests in the Shared Facilities. Each Party and Co-Tenancy Manager hereby elects to be excluded from the provisions of Subchapter K of Chapter 1 of the Internal Revenue Code of 1986, as amended (the “IRS Code”), with respect to the joint ownership of the Shared Facilities. The exclusion elected by the Parties hereunder shall commence with the execution of this Agreement and shall be equally applicable to all Parties. Each Party and the Co-Tenancy Manager hereby covenants and agrees that each Party shall report on such Party’s respective federal and state income tax returns such Party’s respective share of items of income, gain/loss, deduction and credits that result from holding the Shared Facilities in a manner consistent with (i) the treatment of the co-tenancy as a co-ownership of real property (and not a partnership) for Federal and state income tax purposes, and (ii) the exclusion of the Parties from Subchapter K of Chapter 1 of the IRS Code, commencing with the first taxable year of such Party that includes the Operative Date. No Party nor the Co-Tenancy Manager shall notify the Commissioner of Internal Revenue that such party desires that Subchapter K of the IRS Code apply to the Parties and each Party hereby agrees to indemnify, protect, defend and hold the other Parties free and harmless from all costs, liabilities, tax consequences and expenses, including, without limitation, attorneys’ fees, which may result from any Party so notifying the Commissioner in violation of this Agreement or otherwise taking a contrary position on any tax return. The Parties and the Co-Tenancy Manager shall not file a partnership or corporate tax return, conduct business under a common name, execute an agreement identifying any or all of the Parties as partners, shareholders, or members of a business entity, or otherwise hold themselves out as a partnership or other form of business entity. Except as expressly provided herein, no Party is authorized to act as agent for, to act on behalf of, or to do any act that will bind any other Party or to incur any obligations with respect to the Shared Facilities. The employees, agents, and subcontractors of the Parties and the Co-Tenancy Manager, in performing the obligations of each respective Party and the Co-Tenancy Manager under this Agreement, shall not be deemed to be the agents or employees or subcontractors of any other Party or the Co-Tenancy Manager. Each Party acknowledges that while the Parties hold undivided interests in the Real Property Interests, and as such, all Parties would be entitled to control the Real Property and its use, each Party’s right to occupy and use the Shared Facilities is governed by and subject to this Agreement.
2.5 Waiver of Right to Partition or Divide. The Co-Tenants each acknowledge and agree that it would be prejudicial to the interests of the Co-Tenants under this Agreement if any Co-Tenant were to seek partition or any other type of division of any Shared Facilities or Real Property Interests, or to file an action for such partition or division. Partition of Shared Facilities or Real Property Interests would result in substantial and irreparable damage to the Co-Tenants, and is likely to interfere with a Co-Tenant’s ability to transmit power. Therefore, in consideration of such fact and for other good and valuable consideration, each of the Co-Tenants hereby waive and relinquish any and all rights that it may have to seek a partition or any other type of division of any Shared Facilities or Real Property Interests. The Co-Tenants benefit from this waiver in expending substantial funds to construct the Shared Facilities and other improvements, and all Parties agree that each Party shall be estopped from denying the validity or enforceability of the foregoing waiver.
PAYMENT OF EXPENSES AND COSTS
3.1 Easement Payments. Until such time that a Co-Tenant may transfer its rights under an Easement pursuant to Section 4.1 below, the Co-Tenancy Manager shall, on behalf of each Co-Tenant, make the payments due under the Easements, as a Shared O&M Expense (hereinafter defined).
3.2 Maintenance and Repair of the Shared Facilities. Each Co-Tenant shall be responsible for and shall pay for its pro-rata share of the expenses and liabilities relating to the use, maintenance and repair of the Shared Facilities (“Shared O&M Expenses”). Upon DTE exercising its Option, the Co-Tenants agree to negotiate in good faith with each other and DTE any changes required to each Co-Tenant’s obligation to pay Shared O&M Expenses. Upon becoming a Co-Tenant and until such Party ceases to be a Co-Tenant hereunder, the Co-Tenants shall reimburse the Co-Tenancy Manager for all reasonably incurred direct and indirect home office labor and home office out-of-pocket expenses, including, but not limited to, travel, telephone, facsimile, and postage, payable monthly in arrears, in the form of a monthly fixed fee in an amount equal to Five Thousand Eight Hundred Thirty Three and 33/100 Dollars ($5,833.33) (the “Management Fee”).
3.3 Maintenance and Repair of Separate Facilities. Each Co-Tenant shall be solely responsible for and shall pay all expenses and liabilities relating to the use, maintenance, repair, and inspection of such Co-Tenant’s Separate Facilities (the “Separate O&M Expenses”).
3.4 Invoicing, Late Payments. The Co-Tenancy Manager shall deliver a detailed invoice to the Co-Tenants for their respective share of the applicable Shared O&M Expenses for the actual amount incurred for all Shared O&M Expenses. The Co-Tenants shall pay to the Co-Tenancy Manager the amount of each invoice within thirty (30) days after the date of the Co-Tenancy Manager’s issuance of each such invoice. If a Co-Tenant fails to pay all or any portion of any amount owed to the Co-Tenancy Manager under this Agreement by its due date for any reason whatsoever, then such Co-Tenant shall, in addition to such unpaid amount, pay interest on the unpaid amount which shall accrue at a rate equal to the Default Interest Rate from the due date therefor until such amount has been paid in full.
3.5 Ad Valorem Taxes and Assessments. Co-Tenants agree that ad valorem taxes of the Shared Facilities shall be shared equally by the Co-Tenants, and the Co-Tenancy Manager shall calculate such allocation on this basis and include a line item for such taxes in the Co-Tenancy Budget.
3.6 Costs of Repair Work. The Co-Tenancy Manager shall charge the costs of Shared Facilities Maintenance, repair of Shared Facilities, including Replacement Components, and for other work or services provided by the Co-Tenancy Manager under this Agreement that are not included in Exhibit B at Co-Tenancy Manager’s cost.
3.7 Co-Tenancy O&M Budget.
(a) Within ten (10) days after the Operative Date and no later than sixty (60) days prior to the beginning of each calendar year during the Term hereof thereafter, the Co-Tenancy Manager shall prepare and submit to the Co-Tenants a proposed budget for operation,
maintenance and repair of the Shared Facilities for the following calendar year (each, a “Co-Tenancy O&M Budget”), which shall include, at a minimum, the billing rates, estimated cost, based on time and materials and all fees and reimbursable costs contemplated in this Agreement for anticipated operation and maintenance services and repairs to be provided by the Co-Tenancy Manager during each month of the following year, including any Shared O&M Expenses. The Co-Tenancy O&M Budget shall set forth the respective amounts allocated to the different Co-Tenants in accordance with this Agreement. When approved pursuant to subparagraph (b) below, the Co-Tenancy O&M Budget shall be the “Approved Co-Tenancy O&M Budget” for such year.
(b) The Co-Tenants shall give their approval or disapproval of the Co-Tenancy O&M Budget no later than thirty (30) days after receipt thereof from the Co-Tenancy Manager. If a Co-Tenant objects to all or any portion of the proposed Co-Tenancy O&M Budget, the Co-Tenant shall furnish the Co-Tenancy Manager and other Co-Tenant in writing, the reasons for such objections and shall immediately commence discussions with the Co-Tenancy Manager and the other Co-Tenant in an effort to reach an Approved Co-Tenancy O&M Budget. Upon such agreement, the Co-Tenancy Manager shall revise the Co-Tenancy O&M Budget with respect thereto. If the Co-Tenancy O&M Budget is approved by all Co-Tenants and the Co-Tenancy Manager, the Co-Tenancy O&M Budget will be the Approved Co-Tenancy O&M Budget for the following year. If the Co-Tenants and the Co-Tenancy Manager are unable to reach an agreement with respect to the Co-Tenancy O&M Budget prior to the beginning of the calendar year, the Approved Co-Tenancy O&M Budget for the previous calendar year (or the last Approved Co-Tenancy O&M Budget if the Co-Tenancy O&M Budget for the prior year was not approved), increased (but not decreased) per year by the Inflation Adjustment Factor, shall apply; provided, however, that any non-recurring extraordinary expense in excess of Twenty Thousand and No/100 Dollars ($20,000.00) contained in the prior budget shall not be included without the prior approval of all Co-Tenants.
3.8 Other Expenses Caused By Co-Tenants. Notwithstanding the provisions of this Article 3, any costs, claims, losses or other liabilities arising from the actions or inactions of a Co-Tenant in violation or breach of the covenants herein or the provisions of the Easements shall be the responsibility of such Co-Tenant.
3.9 Liens. No Party shall, directly or indirectly, create, incur or permit to exist, any lien on the right, title and interest of the other Co-Tenant in the Real Property or any Shared Facilities. No Party shall, directly or indirectly, create, incur or permit to exist any lien on its right, title and interest in the Real Property or any Shared Facilities except for the following to the extent permitted under such Party’s arrangements with its Secured Parties: (a) any lien for unpaid taxes that are (i) not yet payable or (ii) that are being contested in good faith by appropriate proceedings, or (b) any mechanic’s or materialmen’s lien arising in the ordinary course of business, either (i) for amounts not yet due or (ii) for amounts being contested in good faith by appropriate proceedings, or (c) judgment liens, provided that in each case of (a), (b) and (c) above, so long as such proceeding or lien shall not involve any substantial danger of the sale, forfeiture or loss of any part of the Real Property or Real Property Interest or the Shared Facilities, including the posting of any bond that is required by applicable law to avoid such sale, forfeiture or loss while such claims are being contested. If any such lien not permitted pursuant to this Section 3.9 attaches or a Co-Tenant receives notice of any such lien, the Party whose actual or alleged act or omission resulted in such lien shall cause such lien to be released and removed of record within fifteen (15)
days of such attachment or notice, unless (in the case of any non-permitted lien on such Party’s right, title and interest in any Real Property or Shared Facilities (x) such Party (i) in good faith contests or disputes the claim or claims of the lienholders and the validity of such liens, (ii) promptly commences legal action to remove such lien and (iii) furnishes to the other Co-Tenant and its Secured Parties a bond or other security acceptable to the other Co-Tenant and Secured Parties in an amount sufficient to discharge all such contested liens and (y) during such period the lienholders’ proceedings are stayed.
OTHER RIGHTS AND OBLIGATIONS OF CO-TENANTS
4.1 Termination or Modification of Any Easement. No Easement may be terminated, modified or amended without the mutual consent and agreement of all Co-Tenants. The Co-Tenancy Manager shall notify the Co-Tenants at least one hundred twenty (120) days prior to the time when any Easement must be extended. If any Easement provides for extending the term of the Easement for successive annual or longer periods and if the Co-Tenants agree to extend the Easement for the longer period of the permitted extension, such Parties shall authorize the Co-Tenancy Manager to, and the Co-Tenancy Manager shall, on behalf of such Parties, extend such Easement for such longer period. If the Co-Tenants fail to agree to the longer period of extension, the Co-Tenants shall authorize the Co-Tenancy Manager to, and the Co-Tenancy Manager shall, on behalf of the Co-Tenants, extend such Easement for the lesser time period of (i) annually, or (ii) the minimum extension period permitted under such Easement. Notwithstanding any provision contained in this Section 4.1 to the contrary, if a Party notifies the Co-Tenancy Manager and the other Co-Tenants that it has elected not to extend the term of an Easement (a “Non-Extending Party”), the other Co-Tenants may extend the term of such Easement for their sole benefit. In such a case, the Non-Extending Party hereby grants to the other Co-Tenants the right and option to purchase, for the sum of Ten and No/100 Dollars ($10.00), upon written notice to the Non-Extending Party given within ninety (90) days following the Non-Extending Party’s election notice (the “Option Notice”), all of the Non-Extending Party’s right, title and interest in the Easement or Easements that the Non-Extending Party has elected not to extend. The Non-Extending Party and the other Co-Tenants shall execute, and the Co-Tenancy Manager shall cause to be recorded on behalf of such Co-Tenants, such instruments and assignments as necessary to transfer such Easement to the other Co-Tenants. Promptly following receipt of the Option Notice, the Non-Extending Party shall, subject to applicable approvals from Governmental Authorities, if any, promptly remove all of its Separate Facilities from the real property encumbered by the Easement so as not to incur any other expenses for the other Co-Tenants due to the presence of the Non-Extending Party’s Separate Facilities within the real property encumbered by the Easement. For the avoidance of doubt, following any acquisition of any Easement from any Non-Extending Party by any Co-Tenant or Co-Tenants, the Non-Extending Party’s rights under this Agreement with respect to such Easement shall terminate.
4.2 Standard of Performance. Subject to the limitations or restrictions set forth in this Agreement, the Co-Tenancy Manager and each Co-Tenant shall perform its respective obligations hereunder in accordance with this Agreement, all Applicable Laws, Prudent Industry Practice, and the terms of the Easements. The Co-Tenancy Manager shall perform its obligations hereunder in a manner that (a) does not discriminate against any other Co-Tenants, and (b) attempts to maximize the delivery of energy from all Projects. The Co-Tenancy Manager shall perform its obligations
hereunder in compliance with the Interconnection Agreements; provided, however, that each Co-Tenant shall deliver to the Co-Tenancy Manager a copy of such Co-Tenant’s Interconnection Agreements.
4.3 Party Representatives. On or promptly after the Operative Date, each Party shall by written notice to the other Parties designate an individual representative (the “Party Representative”) whose instructions, requests, and decisions will be binding upon such Party in all matters concerning this Agreement, except that the Party Representative shall not have the authority to amend this Agreement. Each Party shall have the right to change such Party Representative at any time and from time to time by written notice to the other Parties and the Co-Tenancy Manager.
MANAGEMENT RIGHTS AND VOTING
5.1 In General. The actions that the Co-Tenancy Manager is authorized to take pursuant to this Agreement with respect to the Shared Facilities or the Real Property Interests, as well as any actions to implement this Agreement, shall be taken by the Co-Tenancy Manager in accordance with the terms of this Agreement and any limitations or restrictions set forth herein. Except as expressly stated herein, all decisions with respect to the Separate Facilities of a Co-Tenant shall be made by that Co-Tenant. The Co-Tenants shall not interfere in the management of the Shared Facilities by the Co-Tenancy Manager in accordance with this Agreement except with respect to such matters that are permitted pursuant to the explicit terms contained in this Agreement.
5.2 Voting. Each Co-Tenant shall have the right to vote on any matter requiring a vote of the Co-Tenants in proportion to its Pro-Rata Share in the Shared Facilities; provided, however, that each vote shall require approval by the Required Majority of the Co-Tenants affected by such vote.
5.3 Specific Authority. Without limiting the generality of the foregoing, and subject to the limitations of authority of the Co-Tenancy Manager in Section 5.3 below or otherwise set forth in this Agreement, in addition to the authority otherwise granted herein, the Co-Tenancy Manager shall have the power, without further consent or approval of the Co-Tenants, to do any of the following:
(a) To negotiate, enter into on behalf of the Co-Tenants, and administer agreements with third party contractors, or to employ persons, and to otherwise expend monies necessary for the management, operation, maintenance, and repair of the Shared Facilities in accordance with this Agreement; provided, however, that (i) such engagement and any fees paid to such third party contractor thereunder shall be in accordance with the Approved Co-Tenancy O&M Budget or Section 3.6, (ii) with respect to any agreement with a third party contractor that is an Affiliate of the Co-Tenancy Manager, the Co-Tenancy Manager enters into such agreement on an arms-length basis, and (iii) no such third party contractor engagement shall relieve the Co-Tenancy Manager of its rights or obligations set forth in this Agreement or act as an assignment of this Agreement or any Party’s rights, duties or obligations hereunder not otherwise permitted by this Agreement.
(b) To pay amounts that are permitted to be paid pursuant to this Agreement and collect on behalf of the Co-Tenants amounts due in connection with the Shared Facilities, but only in accordance with the Approved Co-Tenancy O&M Budget.
(c) To commit to the expenditure of or spend up to and including Twenty Thousand and No/100 Dollars ($20,000.00) in the aggregate (including the costs of installation,expediting fees, and costs incurred with respect to Section 5.2(d)(iii)) for and on behalf of the Co-Tenants to repair the Shared Facilities due to an Emergency; provided that the Co-Tenancy Manager gives concurrent notice by facsimile and electronic mail to the Co-Tenants benefiting from the Shared Facilities regarding the nature and amount of the expenditure as soon as reasonably practicable after the estimated amount of the expenditure is known by the Co-Tenancy Manager, but in any event no later than the time the Co-Tenancy Manager commits to the expenditure; provided, however, that any expenditure with respect to the Separate Facilities of a Co-Tenant shall be made only with the prior approval of such Co-Tenant.
(d) To replace any component of a Shared Facility with a Qualified Replacement Component without seeking additional consent of the applicable Co-Tenants under this Agreement (i) if such replacement, and the cost thereof, is included in the Approved Co-Tenancy O&M Budget, (ii) if the cost of the Qualified Replacement Component (including installation) is not included in the Approved Co-Tenancy O&M Budget, if the cost of the Qualified Replacement Component (including installation) is equal to or less than Twenty Thousand and No/100 Dollars ($20,000.00) individually or Sixty Thousand and No/100 Dollars ($60,000.00) in the aggregate in a budget year, or (iii) in the event of an Emergency, if the cost of the Qualified Replacement Component (including installation) is equal to or less than Twenty Thousand and No/100 Dollars ($20,000.00); provided, however, if the cost of the Qualified Replacement Component (including installation) exceeds Ten Thousand and No/100 Dollars ($10,000.00), notice of such replacement shall be given by the Co-Tenancy Manager to the Co-Tenants as soon as reasonably practicable after the estimated replacement cost for the Qualified Replacement Component is known by the Co-Tenancy Manager. No other notice of such Qualified Replacement Component shall be required except as such replacement costs may be included in periodic financial and operating reports that may be required under this Agreement.
(i) Except as provided in Section 1.4(a), the Co-Tenancy Manager shall promptly provide notice (the “Replacement Notice”) in writing to the applicable Co-Tenants of (a) any component of a Shared Facility that needs replacement, (b) the proposed replacement component, which shall be a Qualified Replacement Component (the “Proposed Replacement Component”), and (c) the estimated cost (including installation) thereof. If the Co-Tenants approve the Proposed Replacement Component, the Co-Tenancy Manager shall replace such Shared Facility component with the Proposed Replacement Component. If the Co-Tenants fail to approve the Proposed Replacement Component within fifteen (15) days following receipt of the Replacement Notice, the Co-Tenants shall exercise commercially reasonable efforts to develop a commercially reasonable alternative (the “Alternative Proposal”) which shall be presented to the Co-Tenancy Manager within thirty (30) days of receipt of the Replacement Notice, and the Co-Tenancy Manager shall be authorized to proceed with the Alternative Proposal, if any, approved by the Co-Tenants. If a Co-Tenant who does not approve such Proposed Replacement Component or Alternative Proposal can demonstrate to the other Co-Tenant
that the Proposed Replacement Component is likely to have a material adverse effect upon such Co-Tenant’s Project, the Co-Tenancy Manager shall not implement the Proposed Replacement Component or Alternative Proposal without the consent of the Co-Tenant whose Phase will be materially adversely impacted. Notwithstanding the foregoing, if failure to replace such component has caused or could reasonably cause an Emergency, the Co-Tenants agree that the Co-Tenancy Manager may proceed with the replacement of the component with the Proposed Replacement Component, regardless of any objection or failure to consent by a Co-Tenant.
(ii) If the Co-Tenancy Manager installs a Replacement Component, it shall, to the fullest extent commercially reasonable and subject to Prudent Industry Practice: (i) limit any interference with the Separate Facilities and the Co-Tenants’ use of the Shared Facilities during such installation activities; and (ii) except in the event of an Emergency and subject to Section 5.4, schedule any required disconnection of the Shared Facilities during an off-peak and/or low wind down-time period in order to minimize the impact on the Projects of the Co-Tenants; and (iii) provide prior (or, in the case of an Emergency, prompt) written notice to the Co-Tenants of commencement of such construction activities, together with a reasonably detailed description thereof, including dates and times of construction activities and disconnection, if any.
5.4 Limitation on Authority. The Co-Tenancy Manager shall not take any of the following actions without the prior written approval of all Co-Tenants with a beneficial interest affected by the action:
(a) Enter in to any commitments, contracts or other agreements requiring expenditures not included in the Approved Co-Tenancy O&M Budget in excess of Twenty Thousand and No/100 Dollars ($20,000.00) or with a duration of more than one (1) year;
(b) Create or cause to be created any Lien on any of the Shared Facilities or the Real Property Interests, except for Permitted Mechanic’s Liens;
(c) Amend or modify the terms of this Agreement, or any other agreement to which any Co-Tenant is a party;
(d) Perform or omit to perform any act which would cause any person reasonably to believe that the Co-Tenancy Manager is a partner of a Co-Tenant or authorized to bind a Co-Tenant, except as expressly provided herein;
(e) Sell, assign, mortgage, encumber, convey or otherwise transfer all or any portion of the Undivided Interests held by any Co-Tenant, or any components of the Shared Facilities or rights therein;
(f) Borrow funds or otherwise incur indebtedness on behalf of a Co-Tenant;
(g) Procure any insurance coverage that is less than the coverages required by Article 7;
(h) Incur expenses except in accordance with this Agreement and the Approved Co-Tenancy O&M Budget;
(i) Adopt or amend or modify the Co-Tenancy O&M Budget;
(j) Make any offer or enter into any contract, letter of intent or agreement with respect to any zoning classification or other zoning or land use restrictions;
(k) Do any act or that is specified as being beyond the authority of a Co-Tenant, or in contravention of, or that will otherwise cause a Co-Tenant to be in default under, this Agreement, the O&M Agreements and Easements to which such Co-Tenant is a party or any financing documents, investment documents or project agreements to which such Co-Tenant is a party or by which it is bound;
(l) Compromise or settle (i) any single claim, demand, class action proceeding or debt in which the amount of damages in in excess of Twenty Thousand and No/100 Dollars ($20,000.00), or (ii) claims, demands, class action proceedings or debt in which the aggregate amount of damages during any calendar year is in excess of Sixty Thousand and No/100 Dollars ($20,000.00); or,
(m) Procure any insurance coverage that is less than the coverages required by Article 7 hereof.
5.5 Curtailment of Delivery.
(a) The Co-Tenants shall interrupt or reduce deliveries of electrical power over the Shared Facilities if requested to do so by the Co-Tenancy Manager under the following circumstances:
(i) after reasonable notice to and agreement by Co-Tenants as to the timing and duration of the curtailment, in order to maintain, repair, replace, remove, investigate, inspect or test any part of the Shared Facilities or Separate Facilities in accordance with the terms of this Agreement;
(ii) if the interruption or reduction is necessary due to an Emergency; or
(iii) if an order by MISO or a Governmental Authority or regulatory authority with jurisdiction over the Shared Facilities or Separate Facilities requires a required reduction in flow on the Separate Facilities of either Co-Tenant such that a curtailment of the Shared Facilities is required.
(b) The Co-Tenancy Manager shall limit the length of any such interruption or curtailment to that time strictly necessary to correct the occurrence of a matter set forth in Section 5.4(a). Any interruption or curtailment made pursuant to clause (i) above shall be made to the extent commercially reasonable during periods that balance both low or no winds and low energy prices so as to minimize potential loss of revenue of the Co-Tenant(s) being curtailed. Additionally, the Co-Tenancy Manager shall utilize relevant data from the Supervisory Control and Data Acquisition system in place at the time when performing their duties herein.
5.6 Costs of Curtailment and Outages. To the extent any Co-Tenant’s Project incurs any downtime, is curtailed or experiences an outage, in each case with resulting loss of production and revenue to such Project, and the loss is directly and proximately caused by the other Co-Tenant’s actions or inactions, or is attributable to the other Co-Tenant’s Event of Default, then, in any such case, the responsible Co-Tenant shall reimburse the other Co-Tenant for the applicable Net Revenue Losses within thirty (30) days after delivery of notice and supporting documentation of the loss. The Parties agree that payment of the Net Revenue Losses will be such other Co-Tenants’ sole and exclusive remedy for loss of revenue and other Consequential Damages accruing during such period of downtime, curtailment or outage. Each Co-Tenant agrees that the actual Consequential Damages related to the losses in revenues accruing during such period of downtime, curtailment or outage would be difficult to compute and that the Net Revenue Losses represent a good faith estimate of the actual Consequential Damages related to such losses in revenue.
5.7 Disconnection From Shared Facilities. A Co-Tenant’s Project shall be disconnected from the Shared Facilities, and the Co-Tenants hereby authorize the Co-Tenancy Manager to implement such disconnection on behalf of the Co-Tenants, under any of the following circumstances:
(a) upon termination or abandonment of a Project by a Co-Tenant or withdrawal from this Agreement by a Co-Tenant in accordance with Article 9, provided that any necessary approvals from FERC, the MPSC or any other Governmental Authority with jurisdiction over the Shared Facilities are obtained prior to effectuating such disconnection; or,
(b) if the Co-Tenancy Manager determines, in its reasonable discretion, that disconnection is necessary in the event of an Emergency affecting a Co-Tenant with an interest in such Shared Facility; pursuant to Section 10.3 upon the Co-Tenant’s Event of Default; or
(c) following notice from Deerfield 2 of its intention to disconnect the Deerfield 2 Project from the Option Line (as defined in the Option Agreement) and connect to the Line that the Deerfield 1 Project is connected to due to DTE’s intention to exercise its Option under the Option Agreement to purchase, own and use the Option Line (“Deerfield 2 Disconnection”).
In the case of a default for which a proper notice and cure period have already been provided pursuant to Section 10.1 or a real or reasonably perceived Emergency, the Co-Tenancy Manager shall provide notice to the relevant Co-Tenant concurrently with disconnecting its Project or as soon thereafter as is reasonably practicable. Any Project disconnected shall be reconnected when the specific default is cured in full in accordance with Section 10.3(a)(iv) or the specific Emergency is resolved. The Co-Tenancy Manager shall limit the length of any disconnection due to a real or reasonably perceived Emergency to that time strictly necessary to address the Emergency. The Co-Tenancy Manager and each of the Co-Tenants will accept substitute performance necessary to cure the default in full that is tendered by a Secured Party to cure the breach or default of such Co-Tenant. In the event the Co-Tenancy Manager determines that any such disconnection is necessary, the Parties shall provide such plant operational and control data to the Co-Tenancy Manager promptly upon request as may be necessary to implement such disconnection.
In the event of Deerfield 2 Disconnection, Deerfield 2 shall have the right to reconnect to the Line being used by Deerfield 1 and shall continue as a Co-Tenant under this Agreement without being required to comply with the requirements set forth in this Agreement to connect as a Joining Co-Tenant.
5.7 Costs of Disconnection From Shared Facilities. If any disconnection of a Co-Tenant is caused by or attributable to the Project of the other Co-Tenant, or is attributable to the other Co-Tenant’s Event of Default, or is caused by the action or inaction of the other Co-Tenant, the Co-Tenant who owns such Project causing the disconnection, or whose Event of Default or action or inaction caused the disconnection of the other Co-Tenant’s Project, shall reimburse the disconnected Co-Tenant for all Net Revenue Losses arising from such disconnection. The Parties hereby agree that payment of the Net Revenue Losses shall be the Co-Tenant’s sole and exclusive remedy with respect to loss of revenue and Consequential Damages due to such disconnection. The Parties agree that the actual Consequential Damages arising due to such disconnection would be difficult to compute and that Net Revenue Losses is a good faith estimate of the calculations utilized to determine the actual Consequential Damages that would be suffered. If a disconnection that is not due to the actions or inactions of any particular Co-Tenant is necessary, the Co-Tenancy Manager shall implement such disconnection in a fair and non-discriminatory manner, taking into consideration the disconnections previously suffered by the Co-Tenants and such other information that is available at the time of such a disconnection.
CO-TENANCY MANAGER

Deerfield 2 shall be the Co-Tenancy Manager and shall hold such position until the Co-Tenancy Manager either: (i) resigns, or (ii) is removed or replaced as provided by this Article 6. On or promptly after the Operative Date, the Co-Tenancy Manager shall, by written notice to the Co-Tenants, designate an individual representative (the “Co-Tenancy Manager Representative”) whose instructions, requests, and decisions will be binding upon such Co-Tenancy Manager in all matters concerning this Agreement, except that the Co-Tenancy Manager Representative shall not have the authority to amend this Agreement. The Co-Tenancy Manager shall have the right to change the Co-Tenancy Manager Representative at any time and from time to time by written notice to the other Co-Tenants.

The Co-Tenant’s indemnity obligations under this Section 6.2 shall be shared equally by the Co-Tenants. The Co-Tenancy Manager, its owners, officers, directors and employees shall not be liable to the Co-Tenants or any third party for any
obligation, liability, or commitment incurred by or on behalf of the Co-Tenants in accordance with the provisions of this Agreement. To the extent any claimed indemnification relates to Separate Facilities, the Co-Tenant not owning any share of such Separate Facilities shall not be required to provide indemnification to the Co-Tenancy Manager.

To the fullest extent permitted by law, the Co-Tenancy Manager shall indemnify, defend and hold harmless each Party and the Affiliates of each Party, and all of their respective officers, directors, employees, agents, partners, shareholders and representatives, from and against any and all Losses arising out of the Co-Tenancy Manager’s breach of its obligations under this Agreement, gross negligence, bad faith, recklessness or willful misconduct. In addition, the Co-Tenancy Manager shall indemnify and protect each Party from any and all Liens (except Permitted Mechanic’s Liens) filed in connection with the performance of the Co-Tenancy Manager’s services under this Agreement unless such Lien results from the non-payment for services or equipment by a Party or is otherwise permitted hereunder.
6.4 Indemnification Notices; Limitation on Liability.
